  <section id="about" align="center">
      <h2>About</h2>
      <p>Boise-based and Idaho raised, Atticus Kirkham is a freelance author and data scientist. Their studies of esoteric mythology and psychometrics led them to Dr. Carl Jung and his work on archetypes. <br>One fateful day, a witch from the west came into contact with Atticus and read their Tarot. After an intense, hour-and-a-half long session Atticus was enamored by the power of the cards.</p>
    <p>That was three years ago now. In that time, Atticus has studied many forms of alchemical theory. Their purpose is to reconcile the science and the spirit of parascience. <br>They have studied Thoth decks, Rider-Waite, Smith-Waite, oracle cards, and many other divinatory instruments.</p>
    <p><strong>This is what Atticus has to say about their reading process:</strong></p>
    <p>"The Tarot is akin to a conscioius entity being channeled through the deck. The card reader is really only acting as a translator: Explaining symbols, icons, <br>and how they relate to the spread itself. The querent (The person being read) defines their own synchronicity and patterns. <br>There is no psychic exchange but instead a cooperative delving into the unconscious between two parties."</p>
    <p>"Ultimately, the purpose of Tarot and all divination is simple: To bring the actual self closer to the ideal self. <br>It is an act of healing, not prophecy. Prophecy is best left to supercomputers." - Atticus Kirkham </p>
      </p>
